{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nTicket 3b4e's close FAILed twice with the unmet criteria surfaced piecemeal — round 1 named one coverage gap, round 2 a different one — costing two extra Gerrit/CI cycles (changes 526, 527). A FAIL verdict should be complete: every unmet criterion enumerated with its remediation in one pass, so one remediation round can clear the gate.\n\n## What\n- Update the completion-verifier rubric prompt (src/rebar/llm/reviewers/completion_verifier.md) to require exhaustive evaluation: assess EVERY acceptance/success/close criterion independently and, on FAIL, emit one finding per unmet criterion — never stop at the first failure. State explicitly that a verdict naming only a subset of unmet criteria is an incomplete verdict.\n- This is a pass-4/prompt-level change: no verdict-reconciliation or threshold logic changes (rebar.llm.completion.reconcile_verdict stays byte-identical).\n- Prove the behavior with an EVAL case, not a tautological FakeRunner test (a FakeRunner test only returns pre-loaded findings, so it cannot demonstrate the prompt achieves exhaustive evaluation). This spans TWO files that must stay mutually consistent (`validate_eval_spec(strict=True)` requires every deterministic scorer named in a spec to be registered in `eval_scorers.REGISTRY`):\n  - `src/rebar/llm/evals/eval_scorers.py`: IMPLEMENT and REGISTER a new deterministic scorer `enumerates_all_unmet_criteria` in `REGISTRY` — given a case annotated with the set of independently-unmet criteria, it scores 1.0 iff the FAIL verdict emits a distinct finding for EACH (>= N findings, each naming a different unmet criterion), else 0.0.\n  - `src/rebar/llm/eval_specs/completion-verifier.eval.yaml`: reference that scorer AND add a dataset case `CV-two-unmet-criteria` (expect: fail) whose fixture ticket carries exactly two independent AC gaps (e.g. an unimplemented function AND an untested path). ANNOTATION SCHEMA (code-grounded — existing deterministic scorers read annotation fields DIRECTLY from the raw case dict; there is NO `scorer_args` field, do not invent one): the case dict carries a top-level key `expected_unmet_criteria: [<substr1>, <substr2>]` — a list of short substrings, one per criterion that must appear. The `enumerates_all_unmet_criteria` scorer reads `case[\"expected_unmet_criteria\"]` directly (the same way existing scorers read their per-case fields from the case dict) and scores 1.0 iff there is a BIJECTIVE match — each expected substring is matched (case-insensitive substring test on a finding's `criterion` field) to a DISTINCT finding, no finding reused for two substrings — else 0.0. Missing/empty annotation → the scorer abstains (not applicable), consistent with the other deterministic scorers.\n  CLOSE-GATE vs CONFIRMATORY (timing, explicit): the eval RUN is a LIVE-LLM eval that runs in the dedicated `[eval]` eval-CI pipeline (the `external`/eval tier, NOT the per-PR `make test` gate — it needs credentials + the [eval] extra and is not part of the Verified vote). So this ticket's CLOSE is gated by the OFFLINE evidence only — `validate_eval_spec(strict=True)` passing (which requires the scorer registered) PLUS the FakeRunner plumbing unit test (both run in `make test`). The eval run is the CONFIRMATORY behavioral proof of the prompt behavior, recorded when the eval pipeline next runs; it is not a per-PR gate and does not block the close.\n- Additionally add a FakeRunner unit test (mirror tests/interfaces/store/test_completion_verifier.py) asserting the PLUMBING invariant: a multi-finding FAIL verdict survives reconcile_verdict and the close path with all findings intact (guards against regression in the pass-through, distinct from the prompt-behavior eval above).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The completion-verifier prompt (completion_verifier.md, Verdict & findings section) requires per-criterion exhaustive evaluation and one finding per unmet criterion on FAIL, and states that a verdict naming only a subset of unmet criteria is an incomplete verdict.\n- [ ] The `enumerates_all_unmet_criteria` deterministic scorer is implemented AND registered in `eval_scorers.REGISTRY` (evals/eval_scorers.py), and completion-verifier.eval.yaml references it plus a `CV-two-unmet-criteria` case (two independently-unmet criteria). Offline proof: `validate_eval_spec(strict=True)` passes on the extended spec (which it can only do because the scorer is registered). Behavioral proof (confirmatory, in the [eval] eval-CI pipeline — NOT the per-PR close gate): the eval run shows the case's FAIL verdict emits a distinct finding for BOTH unmet criteria (scorer == 1.0). The close is gated by the offline validate + the plumbing unit test above, both in `make test`.\n- [ ] A FakeRunner unit test asserts a two-finding FAIL verdict is preserved (all findings intact) through reconcile_verdict + the close path.\n- [ ] reconcile_verdict and the close-path logic are byte-unchanged (no reconciliation/threshold edits).\n- [ ] make lint passes on the change.\n- [ ] make test passes on the change."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783898330683245001,"uuid":"22b3506e-91d4-4a4e-b2e0-92d06fc69a61"}